(973, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'HIS', 100, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Gateway to History: Frontier in World History', 'Our world is replete with frontiers. We speak of the frontiers of science and medicine, of new or unexpected frontiers in the farthest reaches of the globe, of space as the _??final frontier._?? The term itself implies action: frontiers are to be crossed, conquered, and pushed back. To be on the frontier is to be at the forefront of great endeavors; by implication, the alternative is stagnation and decline. These frontiers of our popular imagination owe much to a theory first articulated more than a century ago. While it has been challenged, historians have since explored how various frontiers_??physical, religious, political, linguistic, cultural_??have defined societies throughout the world. This introductory seminar explores frontiers as barriers and sites of confrontation but also as centers for cultural exchange and interaction. We_??ll look especially at the creation of ethnic, religious, and cultural identities, colonization and settlement, trade, and methods of political control over peripheral areas.', 4.0, '', '', '[W] Juniors and Seniors need signature of instructor', ''),
(974, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'HIS', 100, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Gateway to History: History of the University of Rochester', 'History 100 is an introduction to historical practice _?? what professional historians actually do. It is a requirement for history majors, but we encourage all interested undergraduates to enroll. The class is a small seminar, devoted largely to discussion of primary texts. A final research paper of about ten pages length is required. Juniors and seniors can only register with instructor_??s permission. This section of History 100 will be focused on history of the University of Rochester. \n', 4.0, '', '', '[W] Juniors and Seniors need signature of instructor', ''),
(975, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'HIS', 103, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'The West and the World since 1492', 'A thematic survey of  European history since 1492 focussing on exploration, empire, and cultural encounter between Europeans and others. Subjects to include the conquest and settlement of the Americas, colonialism, the Industrial Revolution, world war, and decolonization. Reading to include original exploration accounts, travel memoirs, documents, and novels. No pre-requisites. ', 4.0, '', 'H1INT002, H1INT003, S1HIS003, S1HIS006, S1HIS013, S1HIS014', '', ''),
(976, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'HIS', 134, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'RUSSIA NOW', 'In this expanded 4-credit version of the 2-credit "Russia Now" course, students will follow current events in Russia through print and electronic sources, and write two short essays and one longer research paper. ', 4.0, '', 'H1MLC001, H1RST001, H1RST004, H1RUS004, H1RUS005, S1HIS018, S1PSC016, S1RST001', '', 'HIS 134, RST 126 (P), RUS 126');
