(1284, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'MUR', 120, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'SYMPHONY AND THE CONDUCTOR', 'Glimpses into the world of standard  performance and an overview of the mթtier of the orchestra conductor. In addition to the ability to read music, and knowledge of basic theory, the participants must have a love for and active interest in symphonic music.  ', 4.0, '', 'H1MUR011, H1MUR012, H1MUR013, H1MUR015, H1MUR016', 'MUR 111 or Permission of Instructor', ''),
(1285, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'MUR', 101, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'ELEMENTS OF MUSIC', 'A course for the student with no previous musical experience.  Topics covered include notation, intervals, chords, and other basic concepts of tonal harmony, with application to the study of a wide range of styles including popular idioms.  Students should not be able to read music. Prerequisite for MUR 111.   ', 4.0, '', 'H1MAS001, H1MUR012, H1MUR013, H1MUR016, N1MAS002', '', ''),
(1286, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'MUR', 104, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'CARILLON', 'Private carillon instruction, weekly 30-minute lessons or the equivalent. By audition only. Permission of instructor required. (2 credits)', 2.0, '', '', '[A] Instructor''s permission required', ''),
(1287, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'MUR', 109, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'MUSICIANSHIP I: LITERACY SKILLS', 'Introduces students to basic musicianship skills. Begins with exercises in pitch matching and basic interval recognition and progresses toward other skills, such as singing simple melodies at sight, sight-reading various rhythmic patterns, and dictating simple melodies and chord progressions.   Prospective music majors, especially those with prior singing experience, typically skip this course and begin with MUR 113. ', 1.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1288, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'MUR', 112, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'THEORY II', 'Continuation of MUR 111. This course continues with chorale and keyboard-style harmony exercises, but also introduces chromaticism, modulation, and analysis of form and phrase structure.  Prerequisite: MUR 111.  ', 4.0, '', 'H1MUR001', 'MUR 111.', ''),
(1289, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'MUR', 112, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'THEORY II', 'Continuation of MUR 111. This course continues with chorale and keyboard-style harmony exercises, but also introduces chromaticism, modulation, and analysis of form and phrase structure.  Prerequisite: MUR 111.  ', 4.0, '', 'H1MUR001', 'MUR 111.', ''),
(1290, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'MUR', 212, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'THEORY IV', 'Continuation of MUR 211.  Explores the theoretical and aesthetic principles of twentieth-century music, especially in relation to earlier compositional procedures.  Introduces basic post-tonal theory, including set-class analysis, transformational theory, and serial techniques. Prerequisite: MUR 211. ', 4.0, '', 'H1MUR001', 'MUR 211.', ''),
(1291, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'MUR', 112, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'THEORY II', 'Continuation of MUR 111. This course continues with chorale and keyboard-style harmony exercises, but also introduces chromaticism, modulation, and analysis of form and phrase structure.  Prerequisite: MUR 111.  ', 4.0, '', 'H1MUR001', 'MUR 111.', ''),
(1292, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'MUR', 113, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'MUSICIANSHIP II', 'This course develops basic musicianship skills with an emphasis of diatonic sight-singing, rhythmic sight-reading, and dictation of diatonic melodies and chord progressions. The exercises and in-class activities are similar to MUR 109 but at a more advanced level. (1 credit)  ', 1.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1293, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'MUR', 114, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'MUSICIANSHIP III', 'Continuation of MUR 113 with an increased emphasis on chrom- aticism, especially simple modulation and mode mixture. The course puts emphasis on ensemble singing and aural analysis. Prerequisites: MUR 113 or permission of theory coordinator. (1 credit)   ', 1.0, '', '', 'MUR 113 or permission of theory coordinator.', ''),
(1294, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'MUR', 114, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'MUSICIANSHIP III', 'Continuation of MUR 113 with an increased emphasis on chrom- aticism, especially simple modulation and mode mixture. The course puts emphasis on ensemble singing and aural analysis. Prerequisites: MUR 113 or permission of theory coordinator. (1 credit)   ', 1.0, '', '', 'MUR 113 or permission of theory coordinator.', ''),
(1295, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'MUR', 115, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'MUSICIANSHIP IV', 'Continuation of MUR 114 with greater emphasis on chromaticism and aural analysis. (1 credit)  Prerequisite:  MUR 114.', 1.0, '', '', 'MUR 114.', ''),
(1296, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'MUR', 116, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'KEYBOARD SKILLS I', 'Introduces students to the keyboard as a vehicle for broader musical development.  Covers basic piano technique, sight-reading of simple chord progressions, realization of figured bass, and basic improvisation.  No prior keyboard training required. Permission of instructor required. (2 credits)   ', 2.0, '', ' ', '[M] Open only to Junior & Senior Majors of the offering department', ''),
(1297, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'MUR', 117, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'KEYBOARD SKILLS II', 'Continuation of MUR 116. Students completing this course fulfill the piano proficiency for the music major. Prerequisite: MUR 116 or permission of instructor. (2 credits)', 2.0, '', ' ', 'MUR 116 or permission of instructor, [M] Open only to Junior & Senior Majors of the offering department', ''),
(1298, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'MUR', 119, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'BEG PIANO:RC NON-MUSIC MAJOR', '', 2.0, '', '', '', ''),
