(1378, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'OPT', 412, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'QUANTUM MECHANICS FOR OPTICS', '', 4.0, '', '', 'Quantum theory topics relevant to atomic physics, radiation theory and quantum optics.', 'OPT 412 (P), TEO 412'),
(1379, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'OPT', 421, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'OPT PROPERTIES OF MATERIALS', 'Interaction of light with materials_?? electrons, phonons, plasmons, and polaritons. Optical reflection, refraction, absorption, scattering, Raman scattering (spontaneous and stimulated), light emission (spontaneous and stimulated). Electrooptic effects and optical nonlinearities in solids. Plasmonics. Semiconductors and their nanostructures are emphasized; metals and insulators also discussed.', 4.0, '', '', 'Undergraduate Quantum Mechanics', 'ECE 421, MSC 470, OPT 421 (P), TEO 421'),
(1380, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'OPT', 429, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'CHEMICAL BONDS: FROM MOLECULES TO MATERIALS', 'An introduction to the electronic structure of extended materials systems from both a chemical bonding and a condensed matter physics perspective. The course will discuss materials of all length scales from individual molecules to macroscopic three-dimensional crystals, but will focus on zero, one, and two dimensional inorganic materials at the nanometer scale. Specific topics include semiconductor nanocrystals, quantum wires, carbon nanotubes, and conjugated polymers. Two weekly lectures of 75 minutes each. Cross listed with MSC 456 & OPT 429. (). ', 4.0, '', '', 'CHM 251 or an equivalent course on introductory quantum mechanics', 'CHM 456 (P), MSC 456, OPT 429'),
(1381, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'OPT', 432, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'OPTO-MECHANICAL', 'The mechanical design and analysis of optical components and systems will be studied. Topics will include kinematic mounting of optical elements, the analysis of adhesive bonds, and the influence of environmental effects such as gravity, temperature, and vibration on the performance of optical systems. Additional topics include analysis of adaptive optics, the design of lightweight mirrors, thermo-optic and stress-optic (stress birefringence) effects. Emphasis will be placed on integrated analysis which includes the data transfer between optical design codes and mechanical FEA codes. A term project is required for ME 432.', 4.0, '', '', '', 'ME 232 (P), ME 432, MSC 432, OPT 232, OPT 432, TEO 432, TME 432'),
(1382, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'OPT', 442, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'INSTRUMENTAL OPTICS', 'Principles and practices for solving problems of optical imaging, optical instruments and optical systems.', 4.0, '', '', 'OPT 441', 'OPT 442 (P), TEO 442'),
(1383, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'OPT', 444, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'LENS DESIGN', '3rd order aberration theory, optimization theory, global optimization, variables and constraints of various lens materials and types. Course concludes with individual lens design projects.', 4.0, '', '', '', 'OPT 444 (P), TEO 444'),
(1384, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'OPT', 447, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'ADVANCED THIN FILM COATINGS', 'Specialty and custom coatings and their scientific applications and business uses.', 4.0, '', '', 'OPT 246', 'OPT 247 (P), OPT 447, TEO 447'),
(1385, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'OPT', 448, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'VISION AND THE EYE', 'How the human eye''s optical and neural factors process color and spatial information includes comparison with the design and capabilities of other animals'' eyes.', 4.0, '', '', '', 'BCS 223, OPT 248 (P), OPT 448, TEO 448'),
(1386, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'OPT', 456, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'OPTICS LABORATORY', '', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1387, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'OPT', 462, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Electromagnetism of Waves', 'Electromagnetic theory as a foundation for classical descriptions of many optical phenomena. Pertaining topics reviewed and expanded upon.', 4.0, '', '', '', 'OPT 462 (P), TEO 462'),
(1388, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'OPT', 465, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'PRINCIPLES OF LASERS', 'Topics include quantum mechanical treatments to two-level atomic systems, optical gain, homogeneous and inhomogeneous broadening, laser resonators, cavity design, pumping schemes, rate equations, Q-switching for various lasers.', 4.0, '', '', '', 'MSC 465, OPT 465 (P), PHY 435, TEO 465'),
(1389, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'OPT', 468, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'WAVEGUIDES & OPTOELECTRONIC DEVICES', 'Propagation and interactions in optical waveguides.  Topics include the Goos-Haenchen effect, coupled-mode theory, pulse broadening in optical fibers, coupling between guided-wave structures and wave-guide devices such as semiconductor lasers, fiber lasers and opto-electric devices.', 4.0, '', '', '', 'ECE 426, OPT 468 (P), TEO 468'),
(1390, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'OPT', 481, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'TECHNICAL ENTREPRENEURSHIP', '', 4.0, '', '', 'Analysis of entrepreneurship from the perspective of start-up ventures and established companies.  A range of management issues is discussed.', ''),
(1391, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'OPT', 482, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'PRODUCT DEV & TECH MGMT', 'In this class we will explore system engineering via the ISO9000 product development process and will illustrate how to use this process to develop both products and research systems that meet necessary specifications.  The first eight weeks emphasize system integration including the development of the product development plans, partitioning of a system into subsystems, quantitative analysis of system performance and the role of prototypes.  The second half of the semester emphasizes the planning needed to take systems to manufacture.  During the course the students will prepare a product development plan on a project that was selected during TEM 440 Screening Technical Opportunities.  \n\nThe course is intended to be interactive.  A portion of the classes will be dedicated to "brain-storming" solutions to technical problems and formal design reviews where the students will review the project plans of other students.\n\n', 4.0, '', '', '', 'OPT 482, TEM 441 (P)'),
