(1414, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'PEC', 582, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'POLITICAL ECONOMY II', 'Modern game-theoretic literature on models of voting and elections. Exposure to techniques and models used in this line of research. Topics include probabilistic voting, policy-motivated candidates, candidate entry, strategic voting, and issues of information in elections including uncertainty on the part of voters and candidates, and problems associated with private information in elections. Both complete and incomplete information models will be covered, students must have a working knowledge of Bayesian games prior to taking this course. ', 4.0, '', '', '', 'ECO 582, PEC 582 (P), PSC 582'),
(1415, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'PH', 101, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'INTRO TO PUBLIC HEALTH', 'Discussion of history and definitions of public health and emerging themes: Public Health Disparities (health and wealth; social justice); Issues in Public Health (lead poisoning; tobacco; obesity; emergency; clean water/air; injury; health systems/reform); and Global Health Issues (globalization and development; maternal and child health).', 4.0, '', 'H1PH001, S1PH001, S1PH003', '[T] Not open to seniors', ''),
(1416, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'PH', 102, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'INTRO TO PUBLIC HEALTH II', 'Introduction to four core areas of public health: biostatistics, health policy and management, environmental health science, and social and behavioral sciences.', 4.0, '', 'S1PH001', 'PH 101', ''),
(1417, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'PH', 206, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'FEMINISM, GENDER & HEALTH', 'This course explores how ideas about gender, race, and sex have shaped past and present approaches to health and medicine. Specifically, we will examine how black women''s bodies have functioned as both subject and object in the disciplinary fields of medicine, law, and visual representation. Topics will include the social and cultural constructions of gender, race, and sex; how gender and race intersect within discourses of feminism and health; reproductive politics; and discourses of human sexuality. This is a writing-intensive course and may be counted toward the University of Rochester_??s Women_??s Studies major, minor, or cluster.', 4.0, '', 'S1WST001, S1WST003', 'BARBER T', 'PH 206, WST 206 (P)'),
(1418, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'PH', 299, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'FIELD WORK METHODS IN PH', 'Seminar for public health students scheduled for  travel to Ladakh to work on the longitudinal tobacco control program with Dr. Chin.', 2.0, '', '', '[A] Instructor''s permission required', ''),
