(1423, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'PH', 397, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'COMMUNITY ENGAGEMENT INTERNSHIP', 'PH 101, PH 102, and PH 103', 4.0, '', 'This is a mentored field experience applying principles of community engaged practice in real world settings.  Students work 8 hours/week with a community agency and attend a weekly 75-minute on-campus seminar for discussion.', '[G] Special application required [J] Permission of School Dean required', ''),
(1424, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'PH', 398, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'PH SENIOR HONORS SEMINAR', 'A year-long research project culminating in a written work supervised by a faculty thesis adviser and the program designated honors adviser.', 4.0, '', '', '[A] Instructor''s permission required', ''),
(1425, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'PHL', 101, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'INTRODUCTION TO PHILOSOPHY', 'Philosophers engage with abstract questions that are fundamental to our understanding of the world and of ourselves. For instance: Is there anything to the mind beyond the physical _??stuff_ѝ of the brain? Do we act freely, or are our actions wholly determined by the state of the world plus the laws of physics? What makes an action morally right or wrong? What is knowledge? Can we ever know, for instance, that we are immersed in an objective reality and not some experientially indistinguishable world of hallucination?\n \n_??In this course, we will explore and critically assess possible answers to these questions and more. Students taking the course will develop reasoning skills that will be useful in a variety of intellectual pursuits beyond the domain of philosophy.\n \n\n', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1426, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'PHL', 102, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'ETHICS', 'In this course we explore a gamut of issues in the philosophical investigation of ethics. Some pertain to relatively specific ethical questions, such as regarding abortion, our duties to future people, and our treatment of animals. At the more abstract end we will consider the nature and importance of moral rights, in what ways ethical thinking can be objective, and how and why we care about ethics.', 4.0, '', 'H1INT007, H1PH001, H1PHL001, H1PHL002, H1PHL003, H1PHL004', '', ''),
(1427, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'PHL', 103, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'CONTEMPORARY MORAL PROBLEMS', 'An introduction to moral philosophy as applied to current topics. Some questions to be explored: Is torture morally permissible in the fight against terrorism? Is it okay to destroy embryos for stem cell research? Can abortion sometimes be justified? How? Is active euthanasia ever permissible? Is capital punishment justifiable in principle? In practice? How far does our moral duty to aid distant strangers extend? What sorts of political and socioeconomic principles are morally justifiable? Do animals have moral rights? How should we understand the meaning and value of life and death? We will also explore related general questions: Is it always possible for a good enough end to justify bad means? What is the relation, if any, between morality and religion? Are there objective facts about right or wrong, or is morality ultimately subjective or relative to cultures or times? Are there situations in which every available action is wrong?', 4.0, '', 'H1INT007, H1PH001, H1PHL001, H1PHL002, H1PHL003, H1PHL004, H1SUS001, N1SUS001, S1PSC010, S1SUS001', '', ''),
(1428, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'PHL', 110, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'INTRODUCTORY LOGIC', 'This course is an introduction to symbolic logic.  We will discuss how to translate arguments into symbolic form and access their validity using various techniques.  Some topics include: how to evaluate argument using truth tables, valid inferences and acies in propositional logic, how to formulate argument in first-order predicate logic with quantifiers, and how to construct simple proofs.', 4.0, '', 'H1INT005, H1PHL003, N1CHM006, N1PHL001, S1INT007', '', ''),
(1429, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'PHL', 118, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'BUSINESS ETHICS', 'Questions and principles of business ethics: moral responsibilities of corporations, truth in advertising, sales practices, bribery, environmental issues, economic justice, nature of the employment contract, whistle-blowing, affirmative action, sexual harassment, corporate organization.', 4.0, '', 'H1PHL001', '', ''),
(1430, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'PHL', 202, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'HISTORY OF MODERN PHILOSOPHY I', 'Philosophical responses of the 17th and 18th centuries to the new science and methodology of Galileo and others. Readings from among Galileo, Descartes, Leibniz, Spinoza, Locke, Berkeley, Hume and Newton on methodology, motion, space and time, causality, perception, the mind-body problem.', 4.0, '', 'H1PHL002, S1PSC010', '', ''),
(1431, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'PHL', 225, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'ETHICAL DECISIONS IN MEDICINE', 'Philosophical analysis of ethical issues in medicine and biotechnology, such as problems arising in connection with the relations between physicians and patients, the challenges of cultural diversity, practices surrounding human and animal research, decisions about end of life care, embryonic stem cell research, genetic engineering, biotechnological human enhancement, and social justice in relation to health-care policy. Papers will focus on analyses grounded in case studies. \n\n', 4.0, '', 'H1PH001, H1PHL001, H1PHL004, H1REL016, S1HLS002', '', 'PHL 225 (P), PHL 225W'),
(1432, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'PHL', 225, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'ETHICAL DECISIONS IN MEDICINE', 'Philosophical analysis of ethical issues in medicine and biotechnology, such as problems arising in connection with the relations between physicians and patients, the challenges of cultural diversity, practices surrounding human and animal research, decisions about end of life care, embryonic stem cell research, genetic engineering, biotechnological human enhancement, and social justice in relation to health-care policy. Papers will focus on analyses grounded in case studies. \n\n', 4.0, '', 'H1PH001, H1PHL001, H1PHL004, H1REL016, S1HLS002', '', 'PHL 225 (P), PHL 225W'),
(1433, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'PHL', 226, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'PHILOSOPHY OF LAW', 'We will consider the foundational questions of the philosophy of law: what is the law, and why should we follow it? Is the law a series of threats backed by force, the naked will of the sovereign? Or is the law derived or derivable from universally valid moral principles? Are these the only alternatives?  ', 4.0, '', 'H1INT005, H1PH001, H1PHL001, H1PHL004, S1INT007', 'One previous course in philosophy.', 'PHL 226 (P), PHL 226W, PHL 426'),
(1434, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'PHL', 226, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'PHILOSOPHY OF LAW', 'We will consider the foundational questions of the philosophy of law: what is the law, and why should we follow it? Is the law a series of threats backed by force, the naked will of the sovereign? Or is the law derived or derivable from universally valid moral principles? Are these the only alternatives?  ', 4.0, '', 'H1INT005, H1PH001, H1PHL001, H1PHL004, S1INT007', 'One previous course in philosophy.', 'PHL 226 (P), PHL 226W, PHL 426'),
(1435, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'PHL', 244, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'PHILOSOPHY OF MIND', 'This course is a contemporary introduction to the philosophy of mind.  We will discuss the nature of the mind with an emphasis on how the mind is related to the physical world.  Some questions we will address include: Is the mind non-physical? Does the mind emerge from the physical? What is the nature of consciousness?  Can we eliminate the mind?  And, of course, can there be zombies?', 4.0, '', 'H1PHL003, S1LIN005', 'One previous course in philosophy. PHL 101 or PHL 145 is recommended.', 'PHL 244 (P), PHL 244W, PHL 444'),
(1436, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'PHL', 244, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'PHILOSOPHY OF MIND', 'This course is a contemporary introduction to the philosophy of mind.  We will discuss the nature of the mind with an emphasis on how the mind is related to the physical world.  Some questions we will address include: Is the mind non-physical? Does the mind emerge from the physical? What is the nature of consciousness?  Can we eliminate the mind?  And, of course, can there be zombies?', 4.0, '', 'H1PHL003, S1LIN005', 'One previous course in philosophy. PHL 101 or PHL 145 is recommended.', 'PHL 244 (P), PHL 244W, PHL 444'),
(1437, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'PHL', 264, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'MODERN JEWISH PHILOSOPHY', 'In this seminar, we will read some of the classic works of modern Jewish philosophy.  Authors include Hermann Cohen, Franz Rosenzweig, Emmanuel Levinas, and  Joseph Soloveitchik.\n', 4.0, '', 'H1REL017', '', 'JST 217, PHL 264, REL 217 (P)'),
(1438, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'PHL', 300, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'SEMINAR FOR MAJORS', 'The central goal of this course is to approach a range of philosophical topics by examining paradoxes that arise in each of them. What do paradoxes show us about our concepts?  Under what conditions do they arise?  How can they be resolved or dissolved?  A subsidiary goal of the course is to help students improve their philosophical writing.', 4.0, '', '', 'Open to philosophy majors and minors only.', ''),
