(1771, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'From Innocence to Experience: Exploring Childhood, Adolescence, ', '"There is more to be learned from the unexpected questions of children than the discourses of men." If what John Locke said is true, then how does our relationship to the world around us change over time? As we get older, do we lose or gain the ability to question existing frameworks of knowledge? What does it mean to "grow up," and is the process more fraught and difficult than we realize? Through writing, peer review, self-assessment, and revision, students will learn to ask the unexpected and trace their own transitions from childhood to adolescence and beyond. Course material may cover selections from children''s and YA literature, such as Lewis Carroll''s Alice in Wonderland and Lois Lowry''s The Giver, the poetry of Wordsworth and Blake, coming-of-age films, blogs and web articles about the millennial generation, and excerpts from works of philosophy and psychology. Assignments include informal written responses with creative options, two shorter essays, and a final 8-10 page argumentative research paper.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1772, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'The Monster in the Mirror', 'We think of monsters as things that go bump in the night, beings who are not like us. But could monsters also be things we fear in ourselves? What can they tell us about our values? About what it means to be human? In this class, we will look at texts in which the hero and the monster might be the same person, where even well-meaning characters can bring monsters into the world. Through discussion and writing on novels and films such as Mary Shelley_??s Frankenstein, Robert Louis Stevenson_??s Strange Case of Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde, and Jurassic Park, we will explore what it means to make a monster. Our discussions will range from definitions of the monster to ways actions might be monstrous to the ethical limits of scientific exploration. The goal of the course is to engage in critical inquiry and to write organized and thoughtful essays using peer review, self-assessment, and revision. Students will practice various kinds of writing, and will ultimately produce an 8-10 page argumentative research paper.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1773, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Not Just a Game: Exploring Issues of Identity in Sports Films', 'Sports movies hold a special place in our hearts. We cheered for the underdog in Rudy, we held our breath during the game-winning shot in Hoosiers, and Jerry Maguire had us at _??Hello._ѝ But are sports films just exciting stories, or do they reveal greater truths about our values and American culture? In this course, we will address these questions by using sports movies as a vehicle for examining issues of individual and social identity. Analyzing films, such as Remember the Titans, A League of Their Own, and The Blind Side, we will consider how issues of race, gender, and the family inform individual values and shape larger social morթs. Students will engage these topics through group discussions, formal writing assignments, and an 8-10 page final research paper. This course will also emphasize peer review, self-assessment, and revision as integral parts of the writing process.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1774, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Being Homo sapiens sapiens: the brain, the mind, the heart, and ', ' 	We call ourselves Homo sapiens sapiens: a knowing species that knows it knows. But why and when does the mind also go on autopilot, as noted by behavioral medicine, neuroscience, as well as ancient meditative traditions? How does this human awareness, or lack of it, inform stance and opinions? In the face of catastrophe, how may mindful awareness of one_??s reactions help reveal important information about oneself, including feelings, needs, goals, relationships? We will consider these questions together by exploring poetry from that of Rumi to Mary Oliver to Derek Walcott and films such as E.T. and Ghost in the Shell. Other readings include studies on how the brain, mind, and heart work subtly to create realities_??ones as fleeting as they can be profound and consequential. We invite everyone to join our interdisciplinary inquiry while cultivating academic writing skills through class discussion, formal and informal writing, peer review, revision, self-assessment, and a final argumentative research paper.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1775, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'From Davy Crockett to Duck Dynasty: Hillbilly Culture in America', '_??We all got a hillbilly bone down deep inside,_ѝ Blake Shelton sings in a recent country hit. Shelton_??s song, along with the popularity of shows like Honey Boo Boo and Duck Dynasty, represent a rise in hillbilly-themed entertainment in American popular culture. What explains the contemporary fascination with the backwoods lifestyle? Can history shed light on this current phenomenon? Finally, what do these cultural trends suggest about issues of race, class, gender, and politics? We will use writing explore the history of hillbilly culture from its Appalachian roots to its current representations in mainstream media. This course seeks to provide students with the essential skills needed to succeed in academic writing and will include several formal and informal writing assignments. Formal assignments will be aided by peer review, self-assessment, and revision, preparing students to develop an 8-10 page argumentative research paper.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1776, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Being Homo sapiens sapiens: the brain, the mind, the heart, and ', 'We call ourselves Homo sapiens sapiens: a knowing species that knows it knows. But why and when does the mind also go on autopilot, as noted by behavioral medicine, neuroscience, as well as ancient meditative traditions? How does this human awareness, or lack of it, inform stance and opinions? In the face of catastrophe, how may mindful awareness of one_??s reactions help reveal important information about oneself, including feelings, needs, goals, relationships? We will consider these questions together by exploring poetry from that of Rumi to Mary Oliver to Derek Walcott and films such as E.T. and Ghost in the Shell. Other readings include studies on how the brain, mind, and heart work subtly to create realities_??ones as fleeting as they can be profound and consequential. We invite everyone to join our interdisciplinary inquiry while cultivating academic writing skills through class discussion, formal and informal writing, peer review, revision, self-assessment, and a final argumentative research paper.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1777, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Technology and You\n', 'It seems impossible to imagine a world without digital technology. Yet, the impact of technology on our lives remains an open question. How does digital media change the way we read, think, and learn? How does it affect how we communicate and relate to others? How might these changes shape academic writing and research? This course explores these questions in a range of material, including public discourse in blogs and videos, and scholarly research in communication and psychology. Through reading/viewing, discussion, and writing, students will engage ongoing critical conversations in order to discover, develop, and defend their own ideas. Formal work includes multimodal assignments, short essays, and a 10-page research paper. In producing work for this class, students will engage in a process of writing that includes peer review, self-reflection, and revision. Course grades are assessed using contract grading, which is based on student performance and a final portfolio of revised formal writing.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1778, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'REASONING AND WRITING IN THE COLLEGE\n', 'Introduces disciplinary writing at the college level by offering instruction in small sections that focus on the act of writing. Provides instruction and practice in clear and effective writing and in constructing cogent and compelling arguments, as students draft and revise numerous papers of different forms and lengths. These papers introduce some of the forms of writing students are expected to produce later in their college careers as well as in their public and professional lives after graduation. The subject of the course is writing, but since writing is about something, each section presents various texts, mostly written, for analysis and discussion in preparation for constructing extended argumentative essays in a final research paper. Students consider the roles of audience and purpose in shaping the organization, style, and argumentative strategies of their own papers, while they learn to become critical readers of their writing through peer critiques and revision/editing workshops. ', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1779, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', '_??American Dreams, American Nightmares: Myths or Realities?_ѝ\n', 'Ever since Christopher Columbus landed at the New World in 1492, the American continent has been considered a beacon of hope and opportunity, a land which rewards adventurousness, determination, self-reliance, and hard work. But are these American dreams realizable? Or are they unrealistic ideals bound to disappoint the individuals who pursue them? In this course, students will analyze how American dreams have been constructed (and deconstructed) within movies such as Citizen Kane and Showgirls, essays by Howard Zinn and Frederick Douglass, short fiction by Harriet Beecher Stowe and David Mamet, and other newspaper reports, advertisements, and scholarly articles. Using these and other texts as raw material, students will develop their argumentation and research skills through class discussions, in-class assignments, peer reviews, self-assessments, and one 8 _?? 10 page argumentative paper that will require extensive research and revision.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1780, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Science and Theism \n', 'In The Blind Watchmaker, Richard Dawkins says, _??_?_I could not imagine being an atheist at any time before 1859, when Darwin_??s Origin of Species was published._ѝ Dawkins, like many, sees Darwinian evolution as a foundation of atheism. Over 150 years after Darwin_??s work, the tension between science and theism remains. In this course students will write an 8-10 page argumentative research paper addressing an aspect of this tension. Through smaller writing assignments and class discussion, we will engage whether and to what extent the tension is substantive or superficial. Perhaps it is possible to be properly scientific while being a theist. If so, how? Or, perhaps one can only be properly scientific by adopting a naturalistic worldview. If so, why? We will engage these questions and others through the writings of prominent scientists, philosophers, and theologians, learning to evaluate arguments. Students will sharpen their writing and argument skills through peer reviews, self-assessment, and revision.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1781, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Adulthood Deferred \n', 'Within the past decade the term emerging adulthood has been used in psychology to describe life between the ages of 18-25 when individuals explore various possibilities, "basking in adult freedoms but unshackled by adult responsibilities." Often portrayed in the literature as a period of inconsistency, this phase seems to defer adulthood as life expectations become increasingly flexible. But, has this new coming of age understanding made living less or more challenging for this age group? Is this sense of emergence experienced across cultures? Across gender? To inform class discussion and writing assignments on this topic, we will examine films such as Step Brothers and books such as Debating Emerging Adulthood. As academic writing is the emphasis of this course, students will sharpen these skills through self-assessment and peer review exercises as they question and critically explore this concept in a series of short papers, all of which lead to the completion of an 8-10 page final argumentative paper.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1782, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Disease & Society \n', 'In 2011, health care spending consumed nearly 18 percent of America_??s Gross Domestic Product. We as a society must make choices about spending, balancing the desire to achieve the best possible health for everyone with the reality of limited resources. Underlying these decisions are ethical and practical concerns, and any policy requires answers to many questions. For instance, which diseases get the most attention? Are contagious diseases in a different class from heart disease and cancer? When may we infringe on someone_??s rights in the name of better health? We will explore these issues using a mix of critical reading, discussion, and writing, drawing from sources that look at the sociological, psychological, linguistic, artistic, economic, ethical, and medical aspects of these questions. Through writing three short papers and a 8-10 page final research paper, you will explore developing a writing process incorporating informal writing, peer feedback, revision, and self-assessment.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1783, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Culture and Learning \n', 'Apprenticeship, metaphoric narrative, and family traditions are all ways of learning through participation in culture. As humans, we constantly acquire new knowledge that shapes how we perceive the world. Which cultural values influence not only what is learned, but also how skills and traditions are taught? How are learning methods different or similar across cultures? Are there universal learning norms across cultures? Students will explore answers to these questions through course readings such as Rogoff_??s The Cultural Nature of Human Development and writing assignments focusing on diverse cultural perspectives from disciplines such as education, psychology, and anthropology. This course emphasizes the importance of the writing process through the use of self-assessment, peer feedback, and revision. The culmination is an 8 to10 page research paper where students will not only demonstrate the ability to develop a debatable thesis and support an argument, but also collect data and report research findings.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1784, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Hypothetical Realities', 'This course will involve critically assessing and writing about the nature and function of hypothetical realities, which for the sake of a working definition we may define as visions of the world that are fictitious but nonetheless deliberately plausible and in most respects consistent with known reality. Particular subjects will range from dystopian writings like Samuel Butler_??s novel Erewhon (1872) to polemical writings on the ethics of allowing children to believe in Santa. In this course we will learn to address a myriad of culturally pertinent questions: How do hypothetical realities help us address our own lived experience? How effective are they at interrogating contemporary culture? Are there dangers to being too invested in a certain hypothetical reality, as in the case of doomsday theories? Assignments will include both informal responses and formal papers, culminating with an argumentative research paper. Course expectations involve commitment to self-assessment, revision and helpful peer feedback.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1785, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Religion, Pop Culture and the Middle Ages ', 'When you think about Christianity in the Middle Ages, do you imagine warnings of zombie danger when crossing church graveyards? What about medieval mystics who drank pus from wounds, and teenage girls idolizing cross-dressing, dragon-slaying virgin martyrs? Medieval religious culture was often loud, gruesome and ridiculous _?? and it_??s never quite lost a hold on popular imagination. But what was the relationship between religion and society in the Middle Ages, and how is that culture represented today? In attempting to answer these questions, students will complete and self-assess short writing assignments, give peer feedback to each other and revise papers for writing quality, culminating in an 8-10 page research paper at the end of the semester. As well as reading medieval texts and examining medieval art and architecture, we will consider modern works from Monty Python_??s The Holy Grail to the video game franchise Assassin_??s Creed. There is a course content warning for works of an explicitly sexual nature. ', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1786, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Stranger in a Strange Land: Narratives of Travel', 'From Homer to modern day travel guides, stories about travel have long captured the imaginations of their audiences. This course invites students to think about the role that narrative plays in the way we experience other places and cultures. How can reading about a space shape our first encounters with it? What do travel narratives reveal both about the place being traveled to and the person doing the traveling? Analyzing writings from around the world, such as those by Christopher Columbus and Olaudah Equiano, movies like Into the Wild and Lost in Translation and modern travel guides and blogs, we will consider how conceptions of race, gender and ethnicity are shaped by travel. Students will engage critically with these sources through group discussion, formal and informal assignments, and a final 8-10 page research paper. In order to develop and refine their own arguments, students will also participate in peer review, revision and self-assessment, as all are vital to the writing process.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1787, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'REASONING AND WRITING IN THE COLLEGE\n', 'Introduces disciplinary writing at the college level by offering instruction in small sections that focus on the act of writing. Provides instruction and practice in clear and effective writing and in constructing cogent and compelling arguments, as students draft and revise numerous papers of different forms and lengths. These papers introduce some of the forms of writing students are expected to produce later in their college careers as well as in their public and professional lives after graduation. The subject of the course is writing, but since writing is about something, each section presents various texts, mostly written, for analysis and discussion in preparation for constructing extended argumentative essays in a final research paper. Students consider the roles of audience and purpose in shaping the organization, style, and argumentative strategies of their own papers, while they learn to become critical readers of their writing through peer critiques and revision/editing workshops. ', 4.0, '', '', '  ', ''),
(1788, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Big Men in Nice Suits: Masculinity in Contemporary Superhero Fil', ' 	From their physicality and costumes to the grand spectacles they perform, the protagonists of 21st century superhero films are transmitting a variety of messages about masculinity_??but what do those messages mean? As these films have attained increasing levels of monetary and critical success, it is important to consider how these portrayals are affecting American culture and ideas about gender. We will primarily examine post-2000 superhero films, screening mainstream properties like The Dark Knight and independent films such as Super. We will be covering a variety of critical texts focused on both masculinity and superhero fiction, including texts by Susan Jeffords and Vivian Sobchack. We will use these films to not only explore masculinity, but also how the process of writing allows us to communicate and test ideas. In addition to smaller writing assignments throughout the semester, the course will require an 8-10 page research paper that will be complemented by peer review, revision, and self-assessment.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1789, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'The Modern Travel Narrative', 'The traveler''s tale is a long-established literary genre: having ventured through distant and unfamiliar lands, the traveler returns to tell their story to a captive audience at home. We will consider how this genre has evolved in 20th- and 21st-century literature and film, when globalization and the tourism industry have perhaps changed what it means to be a traveler, and what it means to read travel narratives. Students will analyze how writers like Ernest Hemingway, Jamaica Kincaid, and David Foster Wallace, and films like The Motorcycle Diaries and Eat Pray Love, affect the way we think about visiting new places and cultures. What rhetorical choices and narrative techniques do these writers and filmmakers use to relate their tales? And what are the political implications of producing and consuming travel narratives today? Students will develop their ideas into argumentative papers (including an 8-10 page research paper) and practice self-assessment, peer review, and revision strategies.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1790, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'REASON AND WRITING IN THE COLLEGE', 'We are constantly making decisions that influence our immediate and future circumstances, yet we rarely stop to consider how it is we make the decisions we do. To what extent is the decision-making process instinctual? How might our personalities shape the decisions we make? What influence does the past have on our future aspirations? In this class we will examine theories of psychology for understanding our own perceptions, behaviors, and motivations. To explore some key debates related to decision-making, we will read Daniel Gilbert_??s _??Stumbling on Happiness_ѝ and Malcolm Gladwell_??s _??Blink_ѝ. Informal writing assignments, readings, and formal papers will work together to inform the final 8-10 page argumentative research paper while offering opportunities for students to collaborate and capitalize on all aspects of peer review and self-assessment. The goal of this course is for students to learn how to construct an effective argument and become confident in their role as academic writers.', 4.0, '', '', '  ', ''),
(1791, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Human Happiness\n', 'What is happiness? We seek it, talk about it, see it all over the news, but are we all talking about the same thing? Philosophers try to understand the nature of happiness while psychologists are concerned with measuring it, but often these projects are isolated from each other. We will look at various approaches to understanding happiness and use critical reading, writing and discussion to think about how the philosophical and psychological projects are compatible, or not. We will use podcasts, popular media and scholarly articles as a jumping off point for entering these debates. Furthermore, we will focus on how writing principles such as audience and purpose function across disciplines by looking at how different fields have approached questions of happiness. Students will be expected to write several argumentative essays, which will go through a process of peer-review, revision and self-assessment, culminating in an 8-10 page argumentative research paper.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1792, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Ethics in Biomedical Research \n', 'Biomedical research continues to extend our knowledge of how our bodies work & how to treat our diseases & injuries. Does this value license any research we wish or are there ethical lines that must not be crossed? Through philosophical readings, in-class discussion, & writing, students will explore these & other puzzles at the crossroads of ethics and science: May we create and destroy embryos in the search for therapies using stem cells? When may we use animals in research? If data came from grossly immoral experiments, may we use it? In the near future, we may be able to enhance our children. But should we? While engaging with conversations in ethics, students learn to extract & critique arguments from readings, discuss them critically, & develop their own argumentative writing. Each student writes several papers during the course, including an 8-10 page argumentative research paper. Writing these papers will be supported by in-class exercises, informal writing assignments, peer review, & self-assessment.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
