(1794, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'The Monster in the Mirror', ' 	We think of monsters as things that go bump in the night, beings who are not like us. But could monsters also be things we fear in ourselves? What can they tell us about our values? About what it means to be human? In this class, we will look at texts in which the hero and the monster might be the same person, where even well-meaning characters can bring monsters into the world. Through discussion and writing on novels and films such as Mary Shelley_??s Frankenstein, Robert Louis Stevenson_??s Strange Case of Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde, and Jurassic Park, we will explore what it means to make a monster. Our discussions will range from definitions of the monster to ways actions might be monstrous to the ethical limits of scientific exploration. The goal of the course is to engage in critical inquiry and to write organized and thoughtful essays using peer review, self-assessment, and revision. Students will practice various kinds of writing, and will ultimately produce an 8-10 page argumentative research paper.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1795, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'What We Talk About When We Talk About Music', 'Whether we are professional performers or casual listeners, most of us engage with some kind of music on a daily basis. If we want to share this meaningful part of our lives with others through conversation or writing, though, we find it is a slippery and challenging process; some have even claimed _??writing about music is like dancing about architecture._ѝ How do we use language to describe the experience of hearing music? In this course, we will explore music writing through articles by authors like philosopher Roland Barthes, musicologist Susan McClary, and music critic Lester Bangs. Our in-depth analyses and comparisons of these styles of writing through informal writing and discussion will provide students with the tools and resources to write about music in two short writing assignments, a research proposal, and one 8-10 page argumentative research paper. Students will refine critical reading skills and writing strategies for these formal assignments using peer review, self-assessment, and revisions.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1796, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', ' 	A Monster at the Movies \n', ' 	The genre of the monster movie has captivated audiences for decades, from King Kong (1933) and Godzilla (1954) to Jurassic Park (1993) and Pacific Rim (2013). Monsters of all kinds have appeared on film, sometimes in multiple versions. This course invites students to consider why these blockbusters are so often popular. What about these monsters is interesting to audiences? Have the depictions of these monsters changed over time, and how? Do they fulfill the same functions across cultures? What do these monsters tell us about ourselves? How does changing technology change how we encounter and imagine these cinematic monsters? We will explore these questions and develop new ones through informal writing, short papers, and class discussion. Each student will refine his or her thinking and writing through peer review, self-assessment, and revision. Assignments will culminate with an 8-10 page argumentative research paper, designed according to each student_??s specific questions and interests.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1797, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'What do people do all day?: Careers in America\n', 'How is American culture and history shaped by work? How does one''s work and search for a career affect individual identity development? What makes "work" into a career? Through popular culture examples including children''s books (eg. Richard Scary''s, What do People do all day) films (eg. Billy Elliot, Office Space, Social Network), and theoretical readings from labor history, sociology, and psychology, this class will explore the definition of work in American culture broadly as well as in individual stories. By engaging students in a constructive learning process including class discussions, critical reading, and formal and informal writing assignments this course will introduce students to academic writing. Writing assignments include short analytical essays and one 8-10 page argumentative research paper. The focus of this course is the writing process and will involve drafting, peer review, self-assessment and revision.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1798, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Language as a Window into the Mind\n', ' 	Language lets us share with others thoughts once trapped inside our own mind, but it_??s also been argued to shape or constrain those thoughts. How central is language to our ideas about the mind? Does language make the human mind special? Are our minds shaped by the language we speak? How should we think about developments in AI and machine translation that have brought machines closer to using language? Do these machines have minds? How would we know? Can we learn about the mind by trying to build a mind? In exploring these questions in writing, we_??ll draw from a wide variety of perspectives, from research in psychology, linguistics, philosophy, neuroscience, & AI, to viewpoints from TV, movies, and literature, especially sci-fi. We_??ll connect concepts from cognitive science to ideas about how to engage in written arguments that are clear and interesting to readers, working towards a research project in which you develop an argument connecting the interdisciplinary themes of the class to your own interests.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1799, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'A Monster at the Movies \n', 'The genre of the monster movie has captivated audiences for decades, from King Kong (1933) and Godzilla (1954) to Jurassic Park (1993) and Pacific Rim (2013). Monsters of all kinds have appeared on film, sometimes in multiple versions. This course invites students to consider why these blockbusters are so often popular. What about these monsters is interesting to audiences? Have the depictions of these monsters changed over time, and how? Do they fulfill the same functions across cultures? What do these monsters tell us about ourselves? How does changing technology change how we encounter and imagine these cinematic monsters? We will explore these questions and develop new ones through informal writing, short papers, and class discussion. Each student will refine his or her thinking and writing through peer review, self-assessment, and revision. Assignments will culminate with an 8-10 page argumentative research paper, designed according to each student_??s specific questions and interests.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1800, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', ' 	Language as a Window into the Mind \n', 'Language lets us share with others thoughts once trapped inside our own mind, but it_??s also been argued to shape or constrain those thoughts. How central is language to our ideas about the mind? Does language make the human mind special? Are our minds shaped by the language we speak? How should we think about developments in AI and machine translation that have brought machines closer to using language? Do these machines have minds? How would we know? Can we learn about the mind by trying to build a mind? In exploring these questions in writing, we_??ll draw from a wide variety of perspectives, from research in psychology, linguistics, philosophy, neuroscience, & AI, to viewpoints from TV, movies, and literature, especially sci-fi. We_??ll connect concepts from cognitive science to ideas about how to engage in written arguments that are clear and interesting to readers, working towards a research project in which you develop an argument connecting the interdisciplinary themes of the class to your own interests.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1801, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Spoiler Alert: Plot Twists in Literature and Film', 'Why does the shock of an unexpected ending provide us with so much enjoyment_??or frustration? Why are plot twists so memorable, and why do we go to great lengths to avoid learning the conclusion of a book or movie prematurely? This course explores the effects of plot twists on audiences and will question whether surprise may be used as a successful device in academic writing. We will investigate the ways in which plot twists defy generic conventions and audience expectations in classic short stories like O. Henry_??s and films like Fight Club. We will use these narratives as a starting point to examine the importance of reader expectations in academic writing. This course aims to develop students_?? scholarly writing so that they may craft cogent arguments through both critical evidence and awareness of audience. Students will engage in class discussion, peer review, self-assessment and revision. Informal writing assignments and short papers will serve as preparation for a final, 8-10 page research paper.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1802, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Justice Without Borders: Writing about Ethics in a Globalized Wo', 'If you passed a drowning child to save $50, you would be considered a moral monster. Are you any better if, instead, you fail to donate money for famine relief overseas? Famed ethicist Peter Singer has argued that most people in developed countries have an obligation to give almost all their income away. In this class, we will contribute to disputes about global ethics in order to learn skills for effective academic writing. Are sweatshops always immoral? What moral problems stem from climate change? And was Singer right? We will address questions like these by learning from the works of contemporary ethicists and economists (such as Singer_??s _??Famine, Affluence, and Morality_ѝ, and Paul Krugman_??s _??In Praise of Cheap Labor_ѝ), and through critical, argumentative writing. Our writing skills and moral judgment will be honed through class discussion and peer review, and you will develop your thinking through in-class writing assignments, essays, self-assessment, draft revision, and an 8-10 page research paper.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1803, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', ' 	_??Devour Up My Discourse_ѝ: Rhetoric and Identity in the Rena', 'How can words be used to persuade or convince? How to present identity? Looking back at texts from an older era can seem abstract, but the authors of the Renaissance were masters of persuasion. In this course, we will look at the ways in which speech can be structured to convey meaning, understand the self, and convince opponents of anything and everything. How did Queen Elizabeth craft herself as a female king? How does Satan construct himself as a hero? How did Galileo try to avoid heresy? How could Iago rewrite Desdemona as unfaithful to Othello? We will be considering these questions and more through examples of poetry, prose, and drama from the Renaissance, as well as criticism and some modern adaptations. Students will learn argumentative and rhetorical skills and use peer review, self-assessment, and revision to improve their academic writing. The course will include several short papers and a final 8-10 page argumentative paper, covering topics from Shakespeare to the rise of modern science.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1804, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Defining Marriage in Modern America', 'Same sex marriage is currently legal in sixteen states and several politicians are voicing their support for marriage equality. Today, we are reassessing marriage as a cultural institution. In this course, students will read texts, complete short writing assignments, participate in discussions, and consider how marriage has been redefined throughout the 20th century. How have social movements and political climates changed the institution of marriage? How have the recent political and social conversations about marriage equality impacted the way we think about marriage as an institution for all people? We will read accounts from scholars such as Michael Warner and Stephanie Coontz in order to consider such questions. Students will use writing as a way to evaluate and make contributions to academic conversations that focus on the institution of marriage and its evolving role in American culture. The course will culminate in an 8-10 research paper focused on a topic related to marriage in modern America.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1805, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'In the Shadow of Facebook: The Internet and American Culture', 'In 2010 TIME magazine named Mark Zuckerberg Person of the Year, calling Facebook _??both indispensable and sometimes a little scary._ѝ Most of us use Facebook without asking how and why it came about, or what it tells us about American culture. But in this class we_??ll bring these questions out of the shadows by examining our own ideas, attitudes, and assumptions through writing. Working backward from the present, we_??ll trace the cultural history of the Internet using Howard Gardner and Katie Davis''s The App Generation and a variety of primary sources. We will sustain an ongoing investigation into what we know and what we think, learning argumentative writing through multiple stages. Class meetings will include discussion of reading material, weekly writing assignments, and peer-review designed to help develop attention to audience, self-assessment, and revision skills. The course will culminate in an 8-10 page argumentative research paper, which students can design as their own cultural history project.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1806, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'What do people do all day?: Careers in America', 'How is American culture and history shaped by work? How does one''s work and search for a career affect individual identity development? What makes "work" into a career? Through popular culture examples including children''s books (eg. Richard Scary''s, What do People do all day) films (eg. Billy Elliot, Office Space, Social Network), and theoretical readings from labor history, sociology, and psychology, this class will explore the definition of work in American culture broadly as well as in individual stories. By engaging students in a constructive learning process including class discussions, critical reading, and formal and informal writing assignments this course will introduce students to academic writing. Writing assignments include short analytical essays and one 8-10 page argumentative research paper. The focus of this course is the writing process and will involve drafting, peer review, self-assessment and revision.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1807, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Contemporary Romantic Love\n', '"Love is all there is,_ѝ sings Bob Dylan, _??it makes the world go round._ѝ It makes us spin, too, even when we think we_??re on firm footing. This course will examine the nature of our dizziness: has love stayed the same throughout history, or is the experience of love in modern America new in its form, benefits & challenges? We_??ll look at cultural depictions of sex, romance, courtship & marriage, as well as changing social & historical conditions, but you_??ll be free to investigate the problem from other angles in your research. Course texts may include novels (Eugenides_?? _??The Marriage Plot_??, Franzen_??s _??Freedom''), films, TV shows, poetry, music, and some challenging critical theory. We will write to explore this topic in a variety of ways, drafting, revising and reflecting in order to clarify, complicate and deepen our thinking. That process will culminate in an 8-10 page research-supported argument, but short assignments, in-class writing, peer review, revision and self-assessment will carry us to that point.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1808, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'American Media Violence: A Psychological Perspective\n', ' 	Many believe that an increasing prevalence of violence in TV programs, movies, music, and advertisements is to blame for violence in our nation today. However, others assert that the influence of the media on real-life violence is minimal. So, how does media violence impact individuals and society? How does it relate to violent and aggressive behavior? In this course, students will use writing to explore questions like these from perspectives within psychology by drawing on class discussion, scholarly articles and examples of violent media (e.g., Grand Theft Auto). With the goal of advancing critical thinking about current issues via the creation and evaluation of written arguments, students will complete several short analytical essays and an 8_??10 page argumentative research paper. Instructor feedback, self-assessment, peer review, and revision throughout the semester will facilitate learning and students_?? growth as writers. NOTE: This course contains violent or sexual content that some may find upsetting.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1809, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'REASONING AND WRITING IN THE COLLEGE\n', 'Introduces disciplinary writing at the college level by offering instruction in small sections that focus on the act of writing. Provides instruction and practice in clear and effective writing and in constructing cogent and compelling arguments, as students draft and revise numerous papers of different forms and lengths. These papers introduce some of the forms of writing students are expected to produce later in their college careers as well as in their public and professional lives after graduation. The subject of the course is writing, but since writing is about something, each section presents various texts, mostly written, for analysis and discussion in preparation for constructing extended argumentative essays in a final research paper. Students consider the roles of audience and purpose in shaping the organization, style, and argumentative strategies of their own papers, while they learn to become critical readers of their writing through peer critiques and revision/editing workshops. ', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1810, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Investigating the Nature of Humor and Laughter', 'Aristotle thought that laughter is what separates us from the beasts, and that a baby does not have a soul, until it laughs for the first time. Humor and laughter play a significant role in all of our lives, yet it is difficult to pin down exactly why it is we find some things funny. In this course, we will investigate the nature of humor as it appears in a variety of forms, from New Yorker magazine cartoons to the droll humor in network TV; we_??ll listen to stand-up comedians and consider the popularity of internet memes. The primary goal of this course is to develop the skills necessary to write clear and convincing prose. Through in-class discussion and informal writing we will analyze how humor functions and why we respond to it the ways we do. Students will develop strategies for academic writing by engaging in self-assessment, peer review, and revision of their work. Formal assignments will include short analytical papers and an 8-10 page argumentative research paper.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1811, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Psychopathic Heroes \n', 'Cold, brilliant, dangerous, personable_??these are just some of the traits of a psychopath we may find as leading characters in TV today. From the less threatening Sherlock Holmes to the predatory Dexter Morgan, popular shows and movies in America depict a broad range of psychopathic figures that challenge our notions of what constitutes a hero. How dangerous are psychopaths really and why do we find these fictional depictions of them so fascinating? By analyzing short stories, TV episodes (i.e., Sherlock and Dexter) and films, we will use all aspects of writing to explore answers to these questions and more. For our discussions and informal and formal writing assignments, we''ll work with scholarly articles, films and film reviews, and primary texts. Formal papers will be developed through a process of self-assessment, peer review, and revision, preparing students for a final 8-10 page research paper on a topic of choice at the end of the semester. Warning: Course covers some content of a violent nature.', 4.0, '', ' ', '', ''),
(1812, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'Minding the Future', 'We are constantly making decisions that influence our immediate and future circumstances, yet we rarely stop to consider how it is we make the decisions we do. To what extent is the decision-making process instinctual? How might our personalities shape the decisions we make? What influence does the past have on our future aspirations? In this class we will examine theories of psychology for understanding our own perceptions, behaviors, and motivations. To explore some key debates related to decision-making, we will read Daniel Gilbert_??s _??Stumbling on Happiness_ѝ and Malcolm Gladwell_??s _??Blink_ѝ. Informal writing assignments, readings, and formal papers will work together to inform the final 8-10 page argumentative research paper while offering opportunities for students to collaborate and capitalize on all aspects of peer review and self-assessment. The goal of this course is for students to learn how to construct an effective argument and become confident in their role as academic writers.', 4.0, '', ' ', '', ''),
(1813, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 105, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'American Dreams', 'The American Dream: this phrase permeates our national discourse, shaping conceptions of success and failure, but we rarely step back to critically evaluate its meaning. What is/are the American dream/s? Is the dream realizable? We will explore these questions by considering and critically analyzing a diverse group of texts_??film, scholarly articles, journalism_??that reflect a variety of historical and disciplinary perspectives. For example, we will view Sugar, a contemporary baseball film about a Dominican player_??s aspirations to play in the U.S., and Forrest Gump, a Hollywood blockbuster about unlikely success. Through discussion, activities, and informal and formal writing, we will embark on an analysis of the role of American dreams in shaping individual and national identities. Students will develop strategies for academic writing by engaging in self-assessment, peer review, and frequent revision. Formal assignments include three shorter analytical papers and a ten page argumentative research paper.', 4.0, '', ' ', '', '');
