(1827, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WST', 100, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'INTRO TO WOMEN''S STUDIES: ABLEISM AND DISSENT: BODY, GENDER, SEX', 'Our culture differentiates bodies according to their capacity to move, think, work, or feel. Historically and culturally this practice has marked those who are less able-bodied as metaphors of evil, objects of curiosity, and inspirational figures. This course examines dissident representation of body, gender, and sexuality in the work of contemporary visual artists and activists who challenge us to rethink why certain bodies are labeled as undesirable. We will look at films, performance recordings, memoirs, and theoretical texts that encourage us to evaluate our ideas about disability and ableism critically and in parallel with key terms in gender and women_??s studies. Subjects we will consider include feminist voices in fat activism, the creation of Barbie_??s disabled friend Becky, and the _??pinkification_ѝ of breast cancer, to name a few.\n', 2.0, '', '', ' ', ''),
(1828, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WST', 123, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'INTRODUCTION TO VISUAL & CULTURAL STUDIES', 'The aim of this course is two-fold: First, to develop an understanding of the extraordinary variety of ways meaning is produced in visual culture; secondly, to enable students to analyze and describe the social, political and cultural effects of these meanings. By studying examples drawn from contemporary art, film, television, digital culture, and advertising we will learn techniques of analysis developed in response to specific media and also how to cross-pollinate techniques of analysis in order to gain greater understanding of the complexity of our visual world. Grades are based on response papers, class attendance and participation, and a midterm and a final paper.  Occasional film screenings will be scheduled as necessary in the course of the semester.', 4.0, '', 'H1AH012, H1FMS010, H1SA002, N1CSC009', '', 'AH 100 (P), WST 123'),
(1829, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WST', 190, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'MIDDLE EASTERN DANCE: FOLKLORIC/BEDOUIN', 'Traditional Folkloric roots of Middle Eastern Dance, focusing on specific Bedouin dance styles of North Africa (Raks Shaabi). Discourse and research will address issues of gender and body image.  Improving strength, flexibility and self-awareness of the body, the class work will include meditative movement, dance technique, choreography and improvisation. No prior dance experience necessary. ', 2.0, '', 'H1DAN007', '', 'DAN 190 (P), WST 190'),
(1830, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WST', 206, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'FEMINISM, GENDER & HEALTH', 'This course explores how ideas about gender, race, and sex have shaped past and present approaches to health and medicine. Specifically, we will examine how black women''s bodies have functioned as both subject and object in the disciplinary fields of medicine, law, and visual representation. Topics will include the social and cultural constructions of gender, race, and sex; how gender and race intersect within discourses of feminism and health; reproductive politics; and discourses of human sexuality. This is a writing-intensive course and may be counted toward the University of Rochester_??s Women_??s Studies major, minor, or cluster.', 4.0, '', 'S1WST001, S1WST003', '', 'PH 206, WST 206 (P)'),
(1831, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WST', 209, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'PSYCHOLOGY OF HUMAN SEXUALITY', 'Survey course on understanding sexuality. Includes such topics as biological sexual differentiation, gender role, gender-linked social behaviors, reproduction issues, intimacy, and the role of social and personal factors in psychosexual development.', 4.0, '', 'S1CSP006', 'PSY 101', 'CSP 209 (P), PSY 209, WST 209'),
(1832, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WST', 212, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'QUEER THEORY', 'Queer theory is a poststructuralist critical theory that arose from the fields of feminist studies and early LGBT studies in the 1990s. This theory not only works to bring non-dominant sexualities under the purview of academic study but also focuses on challenging the supposed stability of the social identity categories of sex, gender, and sexuality. Some of the questions that will be posed within the space of this class include the following: How are bodies that do not conform to binary gender norms received and perceived by both queer and non-queer publics? How have queer identities been informed by other identity categories (such as race, class, nationality, etc.)? What kinds of feelings arise from and attach themselves to instances of normatively resistant forms of gender/sexuality, and how might we understand the political import of these feelings?  How does queer theory intersect with LGBT activism, and what is its relevance in both the academy and society at large? ', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(1833, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WST', 231, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'GENDER & DEVELOPMENT', 'This course examines a range of issues in international development from a gender perspective, with a particular focus on women and girls. Students will review recent literature on gender and development, including how development policies, programs and issues affect men and women, and girls and boys, differently. The course also covers recent trends in economic growth and development across low, middle and high-income countries. Students will have the opportunity to examine development issues, policies, and programs that address poverty and development in a range of sectors including health, education, agriculture, microfinance, and the environment. ', 4.0, '', 'S1PSC007, S1PSC008', '', 'IR 239 (P), IR 239W, WST 231'),
(1834, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WST', 391, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'INDEPENDENT STUDY', 'Students interested in Independent Studies should contact the Women''s Studies Department.', 0.0, '', '', '[G] Special application required [J] Permission of School Dean required', ''),
(1835, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WST', 392, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'PRACTICUM IN WOMEN''S STUDIES', 'Interested students should contact the Women''s Studies Department.', 0.0, '', '', '[G] Special application required [J] Permission of School Dean required', ''),
(1836, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WST', 393, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'HONORS-INDEPENDENT RESEARCH', 'Independent research with substantial supervised research and written work in gender and women''s studies. This research should be directed toward work in WST 397.', 0.0, '', '', '[G] Special application required [J] Permission of School Dean required', ''),
(1837, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WST', 394, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'INTERNSHIP', 'It is the student''s responsibility to arrange the internship with the organization and to find a professor as an advisor for the internship. Organization/Companies currently offering internships are Afterimage, Alternatives for Battered Women, Center for Dispute Settlement, City Council of Rochester, Division of Human Rights, Gay Alliance of Genesee Valley, Monroe Districts Attorney''s Office, Planned Parenthood, St. Joseph''s Villa, Sojourner House, Susan B. Anthony House, TV Dinner/Metro Justice, Urban League of Rochester, Visual Studies Workshop, Wheatley Library Branch and the YWCA. Position descriptions are available in Lattimore 538.  ', 0.0, '', '', '[G] Special application required [J] Permission of School Dean required', ''),
