(2106, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'ENG', 249, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'GENDER AND LANGUAGE IN LITERATURE, FILM, AND SOCIETY\n', 'In the 1970''s the matter of whether gendered discourse exists, and if so what it is, was posed by several researchers. Each of these researchers described how language uses are political, and they insisted that the discussions of gender and language acknowledge the political values that affect the uses of language. Although there is no established "theory" of language and gender, several sources in modern and contemporary literature and popular culture have portrayed situations in which it is possible to relate language uses to political manifestations of gender. A most effective recent text in this regard is the current Showtime series, "Masters of Sex." The reading list has three kinds of texts: (1) The early language studies by Lakoff, Spender, and Tannen; the discussion of the Thomas hearing by Lakoff and by Morrison; the language of law, using essays by Susan Estrich and Patricia Williams; (2) novels that highlight the political valences of language use; and (3) contemporary TV series and films.', 4.0, '', 'H1ENG002, H1ENG016', '', 'ENG 249 (P), ENG 449, FMS 213, WST 253, WST 453'),
(2107, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'ENG', 449, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'GENDER AND LANGUAGE IN LITERATURE, FILM, AND SOCIETY\n', 'In the 1970''s the matter of whether gendered discourse exists, and if so what it is, was posed by several researchers. Each of these researchers described how language uses are political, and they insisted that the discussions of gender and language acknowledge the political values that affect the uses of language. Although there is no established "theory" of language and gender, several sources in modern and contemporary literature and popular culture have portrayed situations in which it is possible to relate language uses to political manifestations of gender. A most effective recent text in this regard is the current Showtime series, "Masters of Sex." The reading list has three kinds of texts: (1) The early language studies by Lakoff, Spender, and Tannen; the discussion of the Thomas hearing by Lakoff and by Morrison; the language of law, using essays by Susan Estrich and Patricia Williams; (2) novels that highlight the political valences of language use; and (3) contemporary TV series and films.', 4.0, '', 'H1ENG002, H1ENG016', '', 'ENG 249 (P), ENG 449, FMS 213, WST 253, WST 453'),
(2108, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'AH', 307, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'RHETORIC OF THE FRAME', 'The task of any discussion of frames and framing in the visual arts whether in painting, sculpture, film, performance, architecture, graphic novels and cartoon strips, or digital media - is first and foremost to counter the tendency of framing devices to invisibility with respect to the artwork they supposedly contain. We see the work, but we do not see the frame. It is against this tendency to ignore the frame that this seminar is directed. At first glance the frame may seem to be as unproblematic. Starting from a consideration of the foundational texts of frame theory in the philosophy of Immanuel Kant, we will examine the discursive limits of the material and non-material border in the writings of, among others, Mayer Schapiro, Martin Heidegger, Jean-Claude Lebensztejn, Louis Marin, Craig Owens, and Jacques Derrida.', 4.0, '', '', '', 'AH 307 (P), AH 507, ENG 541'),
