(2120, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'POR', 102, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'ELEMENTARY PORTUGUESE II', 'Portuguese 102 is the second course of the elementary sequence. The general goal of the course is to develop basic language skills. During this course, students will:\n- Continue to build a vocabulary base in order to increase language skills;\n- Continue to use acquired vocabulary and grammatical structures;\n- Develop knowledge of the grammar structures associated with, but not limited to: talking about events in the present; talking about completed past events; expressing continuing events; describing daily routines and habits;\n- Listen to passages or conversations and discuss their content;\n- Read authentic texts and discuss their content;\n- Write paragraphs and short compositions using acquired vocabulary and grammatical structures;\n- Engage in and sustain face-to-face conversation with others about topics studied.', 4.0, '', '', '', ''),
(2121, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'AAS', 288, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'History of the American South, 1896-1946', '"Blue States! Red States! What are the political consequences of the region''s close attachment to family, religion, community and, most of all, a distinctive interpretation of the nation''s history? Despite the widespread economic development since the 1900s, why is the South still associated with social and intellectual backwardness, violence, racism, and political conservatism? Although these and other characteristics (real or imagined) are rooted in the long history of the South, they are also shaped by more recent events. This course will examine these issues in the search of answers to the question: "Why are most "red states_ѝ located in the South"', 4.0, '', 'S1HIS002, S1HIS008', '', 'AAS 288, HIS 268 (P), HIS 268W'),
(2122, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'REL', 261, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'African Diaspora in Latin America', 'This upper-level seminar will analyze the arrival of over 6 million Africans to Latin America and their impact on the Portuguese and Spanish societies of the Western Hemisphere from 1500 to the present. We will properly begin the study the African Diaspora in Latin America by studying the transition from Indigenous slavery to African slavery in Bahia, Brazil. The following weeks will cover the history of free and enslaved people of African descent in Mexico, Cuba and Peru during the colonial period. We will end the course by studying the criminalization and gradual acceptance of capoeira and candomblթ in South America, and especially Brazil.', 4.0, '', 'S1HIS002, S1HIS003, S1HIS019', '', 'AAS 251, HIS 251 (P), HIS 251W, REL 261'),
(2123, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'HIS', 222, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'The Enlightenment', 'The Enlightenment - the structure of ideas typical of eighteenth century Europe and the Americas, shaped and was shaped by increasing globalisation and the clash of cultures between whites and indigenous peoples. Explosive questioning of religion, political justice and gender were also the consequence of these global encounters. This is a text-based course, emphasising close reading skills.', 4.0, '', 'S1HIS003, S1HIS006', '', 'HIS 222 (P), HIS 222W'),
