(2226, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WRT', 396, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'RESRCH PAPER WRITING IN BIO', 'Invites native or near-native speakers of English to serve as TAs in WRT 101, ESOL Speaking & Listening I.  TAs will participate and lead in small group discussions assisting ESOL students with their learning and class projects.  The objective of this course is for classroom partners to create a fun, social, academic atmosphere in which ESOL students can improve their English speaking and listening skills, make friends, and share cultural knowledge.  Any University of Rochester undergraduate student with an interest in education, international relations, and teaching English to international students may apply for this course.  This course meets once a week, and TAs are expected to maintain professionalism and come to class prepared for the daily lessons.  Instructor''s permission is required to enroll in this course.', 1.0, '', '', '', 'BIO 396W, WRT 396 (P)'),
(2227, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'BIO', 396, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'RESRCH PAPER WRITING IN BIO', 'Invites native or near-native speakers of English to serve as TAs in WRT 101, ESOL Speaking & Listening I.  TAs will participate and lead in small group discussions assisting ESOL students with their learning and class projects.  The objective of this course is for classroom partners to create a fun, social, academic atmosphere in which ESOL students can improve their English speaking and listening skills, make friends, and share cultural knowledge.  Any University of Rochester undergraduate student with an interest in education, international relations, and teaching English to international students may apply for this course.  This course meets once a week, and TAs are expected to maintain professionalism and come to class prepared for the daily lessons.  Instructor''s permission is required to enroll in this course.', 1.0, '', '', '', 'BIO 396W, WRT 396 (P)'),
(2228, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'PHL', 241, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'AESTHETICS', 'Studies the history of _??aesthetic_ѝ thought_??namely the philosophical reflection on the concepts of beauty, taste, and sublimity, on our affective response to art and nature, and on the role of art and the artist in society_??from Plato to the present, with particular emphasis on how it relates to questions of epistemology, anthropology, ethics, ontology, and politics. Readings from Plato, Aristotle, Longinus, Burke, Kant, Hegel, Heidegger, Adorno, Sartre, Merleau-Ponty, Foucault, Lyotard, Derrida, RanciՌre. Conducted in English.', 4.0, '', '', '', 'AH 241, AH 441, CLT 280, CLT 480, ENG 240, ENG 440, FR 265 (P), FR 465, PHL 241, PHL 441'),
(2229, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'PHL', 441, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'AESTHETICS', 'Studies the history of _??aesthetic_ѝ thought_??namely the philosophical reflection on the concepts of beauty, taste, and sublimity, on our affective response to art and nature, and on the role of art and the artist in society_??from Plato to the present, with particular emphasis on how it relates to questions of epistemology, anthropology, ethics, ontology, and politics. Readings from Plato, Aristotle, Longinus, Burke, Kant, Hegel, Heidegger, Adorno, Sartre, Merleau-Ponty, Foucault, Lyotard, Derrida, RanciՌre. Conducted in English.', 4.0, '', '', '', 'AH 241, AH 441, CLT 280, CLT 480, ENG 240, ENG 440, FR 265 (P), FR 465, PHL 241, PHL 441'),
(2230, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'WST', 253, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'GENDER AND LANGUAGE IN LITERATURE, FILM, AND SOCIETY\n', 'In the 1970''s the matter of whether gendered discourse exists, and if so what it is, was posed by several researchers. Each of these researchers described how language uses are political, and they insisted that the discussions of gender and language acknowledge the political values that affect the uses of language. Although there is no established "theory" of language and gender, several sources in modern and contemporary literature and popular culture have portrayed situations in which it is possible to relate language uses to political manifestations of gender. A most effective recent text in this regard is the current Showtime series, "Masters of Sex." The reading list has three kinds of texts: (1) The early language studies by Lakoff, Spender, and Tannen; the discussion of the Thomas hearing by Lakoff and by Morrison; the language of law, using essays by Susan Estrich and Patricia Williams; (2) novels that highlight the political valences of language use; and (3) contemporary TV series and films.', 4.0, '', 'H1ENG002, H1ENG016', '', 'ENG 249 (P), ENG 449, FMS 213, WST 253, WST 453'),
(2231, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'ENG', 240, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'AESTHETICS', 'Studies the history of _??aesthetic_ѝ thought_??namely the philosophical reflection on the concepts of beauty, taste, and sublimity, on our affective response to art and nature, and on the role of art and the artist in society_??from Plato to the present, with particular emphasis on how it relates to questions of epistemology, anthropology, ethics, ontology, and politics. Readings from Plato, Aristotle, Longinus, Burke, Kant, Hegel, Heidegger, Adorno, Sartre, Merleau-Ponty, Foucault, Lyotard, Derrida, RanciՌre. Conducted in English.', 4.0, '', '', '', 'AH 241, AH 441, CLT 280, CLT 480, ENG 240, ENG 440, FR 265 (P), FR 465, PHL 241, PHL 441'),
(2232, 'Arts, Sciences, and Engineering', 'BIO', 151, 'MAIN_COURSE', 'INTRODUCTION TO BIOCHEMISTRY LAB', 'Complements Biochemistry lecture.  Experimental design and data analysis using enzyme assays, electrophoretic gels, antibodies, and light microscopy.', 1.0, '', '', 'One year of introductory biology and chemistry (e.g. BIO 110 & 111, CHM 131 & 132). Genetics (e.g. BIO 198 or BIO 190) recommended', ''),
